  "opinion": "As a 28-year-old electrician living in Rome, I spend about an hour daily on social media, and dealing with fake content is a real headache that adds to my struggles with depression. My high extraversion means I enjoy connecting with people online, but my low agreeableness makes me skeptical and quick to call out nonsense when I see it. With moderate conscientiousness, I try to be responsible, but my high neuroticism often leaves me feeling overwhelmed by the constant stream of misinformation, which can spiral my mood downward. Given my low openness, I stick to what I know—like my hobbies of gardening, birdwatching, rock climbing, volunteering, and cinema—and avoid diving into unfamiliar topics that might be full of lies. To manage fake content, I focus on practical steps: I check sources before sharing anything, especially since my education is upper secondary and I value straightforward facts. I rely on trusted news outlets and fact-checking websites, ignoring sensational posts that play on emotions. In my daily hour online, I limit my exposure by curating my feeds to follow only reliable accounts related to my interests and work. As a native-born Italian, I see how fake news can spread locally, so I talk to friends and family in person to verify things, using my extraversion to foster real conversations instead of online arguments. My depression makes me sensitive to negative content, so I actively avoid engaging with trolls or controversial posts, prioritizing my mental health by stepping away when things get too heated. Ultimately, I believe social media platforms need to do more to filter out fake content, but until then, it's on us users to stay vigilant and protect our well-being by being selective and critical.",
